On Oct 24, 2012, at 9:48 AM, Michael Dewberry <michael.dewberry@gmail.com> wrote:

> I strongly disagree.  Commodification, in my personal understanding of the
> ten principles, comes from treating people/objects/ideas/moments of time as
> nothing more than interchangeable functional units rather than the
> constantly-dying ephemeral beautiful snowflake-whatevers that they are.
> De/commodification is a feature of the overall design of an event; it
> doesn't solely hinge on the color of one or two numbers on a spreadsheet.
> 
> A for-profit enterprise or event has more incentives to commodify aspects
> of its operation, but that's not the same as saying that for-profit
> necessarily causes it.  You can have profit without commodification, and
> not-for-profit events have plenty of incentives to commoditize as well.
> 
> In my mind this is a non-controversy, as anyone who complains about event
> postings that have an obvious burner connection, and are of reasonable
> frequency (one a month or less) is just being a stick-in-the-mud.
> 
> 
> On Wed, Oct 24, 2012 at 9:22 AM, Sarah Ficca <sf@sarahficca.com> wrote:
> 
>> In my opinion any for profit event should not be promoted on this list, as
>> it conflicts with the decommodification (spelling???) idea.
